ğŸ§  1. Business Problem Definition

Businesses often face challenges in understanding customer behavior and performance drivers.

This project focuses on answering key business questions such as:

Which products perform best based on customer ratings?

Which customer age groups generate the most revenue?

How does subscription status affect customer distribution?

What purchasing patterns emerge across product categories?

Clearly defining these questions helped guide every technical decision in the analysis.

ğŸ—‚ï¸ 2. Dataset Overview (Raw Data)

The dataset represents customer behavior data, including:

Customer demographics (age, gender)

Product and category information

Purchase frequency

Review ratings

Subscription status

Payment and shipping methods

Initial Data Challenges

Missing values

Categorical variables in text format

Columns not directly suitable for analysis

Understanding the structure and quality of raw data was essential before moving forward.

ğŸ§¹ 3. Data Cleaning & Feature Engineering (Python)
Tools Used

Python

Pandas

NumPy

Key Steps
3.1 Handling Missing Values

Missing review ratings were filled using category-level median values to preserve realistic distributions.

3.2 Feature Engineering

New analytical features were created:

Age Group

Customers were grouped into quartiles:

Young Adult

Adult

Middle-aged

Senior

Purchase Frequency (Days)

Textual frequencies (Weekly, Monthly, Annually, etc.) were converted into numeric day values.

These transformations made the dataset analysis-ready and easier to interpret.

ğŸ›¢ï¸ 4. Database Storage (MySQL)

After cleaning, the dataset was exported from the Python notebook and stored in MySQL.

Why MySQL?

Simulates real-world production data storage

Enables scalable and efficient querying

Separates data processing from analytical querying

This step strengthened understanding of how analytics workflows integrate with databases in industry systems.

ğŸ§® 5. SQL-Based Analysis

SQL was used to answer the defined business questions directly at the database level.

SQL Concepts Applied

GROUP BY

AVG()

ORDER BY

LIMIT

Sample Insights

Identified Top 5 products based on average customer ratings

Analyzed revenue distribution by age group

Compared performance across product categories

SQL enabled fast, structured, and scalable analysis.

